ted chairman of president eisenhowers committee on international information activities often known inside the beltway as the jackson committee  which led to creation of the us information agency usia in december  jackson resigned from j h whitney  co and was named special assistant to the secretary of state john foster dulles to attend the  big four talks in geneva in february  jackson was appointed special assistant to president eisenhower on psychological warfare succeeding nelson rockefeller jackson served briefly as united states national security adviser from september   until january   personal lifeedit jacksons first wife elizabeth lyman married  was the exwife of thomas rice of dover she brought two children thomas rice jr and lyman rice to their marriage jackson and elizabeth had two more sons william harding jackson jr and richard lee jackson they divorced in  after jackson returned from world war ii at age  jackson was elected the youngest president to serve  on the board of directors of the society of the new york hospital one of americas oldest hospitals founded by king george iii in  and was nominated to the national academy of sciences after the war jackson was elected to the boards of bankers trust the john hay whitney foundation the new york hospital for special surgery and the menninger foundation in  jackson married mary pitcairn the daughter of norman b pitcairn a former president of the wabash railroad they had two sons together bruce p jackson and howell e jackson after they divorced around  keating married another new york lawyer wendell davis who died in  she married a third time to us senator and former ambassador to israel kenneth keating thus becoming mary pitcairn jackson davis keating deathedit jackson died on september   in tucson arizona at age  he is interred at mount olivet cemetery in nashville tennessee referencesedit  a b c william h jackson dead at  former cia deputy director new york times september     a b reference the centra